{'summarized_nodes': [{'title': 'Q-balls', 'summary': 'A type of non-topological soliton in field theory, characterized by its charge and stability properties. Q-balls can decay into various particles, including fermions and scalars, and are formed from the fragmentation of the Affleck-Dine (AD) condensate. They play a significant role in cosmology, particularly in processes like Big Bang Nucleosynthesis (BBN).', 'original_ids': ['Q-balls', 'Q-ball', 'Q/MiΝusballs', 'Q/MiΝusball'], 'type': 'Particle', 'keywords': ['soliton', 'decay', 'cosmology', 'BBN']}, {'title': 'Affleck-Dine condensate', 'summary': 'A type of condensate in the context of the Affleck-Dine mechanism, involved in the dynamics of baryon asymmetry generation. The AD condensate is unstable with respect to spatial perturbations and leads to the formation of Q-balls through fragmentation.', 'original_ids': ['AD condensate', 'AD field'], 'type': 'Concept', 'keywords': ['baryon asymmetry', 'fragmentation', 'instability']}, {'title': 'BBN', 'summary': 'Big Bang Nucleosynthesis, a key event in cosmology where light elements were formed in the early universe. The decay of Q-balls must occur before BBN to avoid spoiling predictions.', 'original_ids': ['BBN', 'BBNb/OverTilde'], 'type': 'Event', 'keywords': ['nucleosynthesis', 'early universe', 'light elements']}, {'title': 'Gravitinos', 'summary': 'Particles produced in the decay chain of Q-balls, which may become overabundant due to the decay processes involving next-to-lightest supersymmetric particles (NLSPs).', 'original_ids': ['Gravitinos'], 'type': 'Particle', 'keywords': ['decay', 'supersymmetry', 'overabundance']}, {'title': 'NLSP', 'summary': 'Next-to-lightest supersymmetric particle in the decay chain of Q-balls, which can affect the density of gravitinos and play a role in cosmological models.', 'original_ids': ['NLSP', 'NLSPs'], 'type': 'Particle', 'keywords': ['supersymmetry', 'decay', 'cosmology']}, {'title': 'Operator', 'summary': 'An operator that lifts the flat direction in the potential and is involved in the dynamics of various theoretical models, including the Affleck-Dine mechanism.', 'original_ids': ['Operator'], 'type': 'Mathematical Object', 'keywords': ['theory', 'potential', 'dynamics']}], 'summarized_relationships': [{'source': 'Q-balls', 'target': 'Affleck-Dine condensate', 'relation_type': 'FORMED_FROM', 'weight': 3, 'original_relationships': ['AD condensate->Q-balls(FRAGMENTATION)', 'Q-balls->AD condensate(FORMED_FROM)']}, {'source': 'Q-balls', 'target': 'BBN', 'relation_type': 'DECAY_BEFORE', 'weight': 2, 'original_relationships': ['Q-balls->BBN(MUST_DECAY_BEFORE)', 'BBNb/OverTilde->thermal NLSP(INVOLVES_DECAY)']}, {'source': 'Q-balls', 'target': 'Gravitinos', 'relation_type': 'DECAY_INTO', 'weight': 2, 'original_relationships': ['Q-balls->NLSP(DECAY_INTO)', 'NLSP->Gravitinos(DECAY_INTO)']}, {'source': 'NLSP', 'target': 'Gravitinos', 'relation_type': 'DECAY_INTO', 'weight': 1, 'original_relationships': ['NLSP->Gravitinos(DECAY_INTO)']}, {'source': 'Operator', 'target': 'Q-balls', 'relation_type': 'INFLUENCES', 'weight': 1, 'original_relationships': ['Operator->Q-balls(INFLUENCES)']}]}